; contingency-dsl v1.x — Core-Stateful Grammar
;
; Additive grammar extension for the Core-Stateful layer.
; Core-Stateful schedules have criteria computed from runtime state
; (response history, trial outcomes, elapsed time as continuous function),
; as opposed to Core schedules whose criteria are literal values.
;
; All parameters are declarative (determined at parse time).
; Evaluation of criteria is delegated to the runtime (contingency-core).
;
; This file defines production rules to be appended to schema/core/grammar.ebnf.
; No existing Core production rules are modified.
;
; Integration point (additive to Core grammar):
;   modifier ::= dr_mod | pr_mod | repeat | lag_mod | pctl_mod
;
; Reference: RFC_CORE_STATEFUL_2026-04-13.md
;            .local/percentile/RFC.md

; =====================================================================
; §1. Percentile Schedule — Platt (1973); Galbicka (1994)
; =====================================================================
;
; A differential reinforcement procedure in which the criterion is
; dynamically computed from the subject's recent response distribution.
; Only responses meeting a specified percentile of the distribution
; on a given response dimension are reinforced.
;
; Syntax:
;   Pctl(IRT, 50)                            -- minimal
;   Pctl(IRT, 25, window=30)                 -- with explicit window
;   Pctl(latency, 75, window=50, dir=above)  -- fully specified
;
; Positional arguments:
;   1. pctl_target (required): response dimension to measure
;   2. pctl_rank   (required): percentile threshold (integer 0–100)
;
; Keyword arguments:
;   window (optional): positive integer, default 20
;   dir    (optional): "below" | "above", default "below"
;
; LL(2) disambiguation:
;   After "Pctl" token, expect "(". Inside parentheses:
;   - First argument: pctl_target (one of the enumerated identifiers)
;   - After comma: pctl_rank (number)
;   - After comma: peek — if IDENT followed by "=", parse as pctl_kw_arg
;
; Platt, J. R. (1973). Percentile reinforcement: Paradigms for experimental
;   analysis of response shaping. In G. H. Bower (Ed.), The psychology of
;   learning and motivation (Vol. 7, pp. 271-296). Academic Press.
;
; Galbicka, G. (1994). Shaping in the 21st century: Moving percentile
;   schedules into applied settings. Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis,
;   27(4), 739-760. https://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1994.27-739

pctl_mod        ::= "Pctl" "(" pctl_target "," pctl_rank ("," pctl_kw_arg)* ")"

pctl_target     ::= "IRT"
                  | "latency"
                  | "duration"
                  | "force"
                  | "rate"

pctl_rank       ::= number                          -- integer 0–100 (semantic constraint P1)

pctl_kw_arg     ::= "window" "=" number              -- positive integer (semantic constraint P2)
                  | "dir" "=" pctl_dir

pctl_dir        ::= "below" | "above"

; === Reserved words (additive to grammar.ebnf `reserved`) ===

; reserved      ::= ... (existing)
;                 | "Pctl"
;                 | pctl_target                       -- IRT, latency, duration, force, rate
;                 | "window" | "dir"
;                 | pctl_dir                          -- below, above
;
; Note: pctl_target values other than "IRT" begin with lowercase letters.
; They appear only inside Pctl(...) parentheses, so parser context
; disambiguates from let-binding identifiers. A let-binding named
; "latency" at top level does NOT collide because pctl_target is
; parsed only after the "Pctl" "(" token sequence.

; === Semantic constraints ===
;
; P1. pctl_rank must be an integer in [0, 100].
;     Non-integer or out-of-range → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_RANK).
;
; P2. pctl_window (if specified) must be a positive integer (≥ 1).
;     Zero, negative, or non-integer → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_WINDOW).
;     Omission → default value 20.
;
; P3. pctl_target must be one of the enumerated values.
;     Unknown target → SemanticError (PCTL_UNKNOWN_TARGET).
;
; P4. pctl_dir (if specified) must be "below" or "above".
;     Unknown dir → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_DIR).
;     Omission → default value "below".
;
; P5. pctl_rank must NOT carry a time unit.
;     `Pctl(IRT, 50s)` → SemanticError (PCTL_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: rank is a dimensionless percentile, not a temporal quantity.
;
; P6. Duplicate keyword arguments → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_PCTL_KW_ARG).
;     E.g., `Pctl(IRT, 50, window=20, window=30)` → error.
;
; W1. pctl_rank == 0 or 100 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_EXTREME_RANK).
;     Rationale: rank=0 reinforces all responses (CRF equivalent),
;     rank=100 reinforces no responses (EXT equivalent).
;
; W2. pctl_window < 5 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_SMALL_WINDOW).
;     Rationale: distribution stability. Platt (1973) recommended window ≥ 20.
;
; W3. pctl_window > 100 → Linter WARNING (PCTL_LARGE_WINDOW).
;     Rationale: adaptiveness degrades. Research typically uses 10–50.
